Writing down my thoughts and learning points after I complete the project:

Summary:
Overall the project was fun, I got to challenge myself on git, although not extremely, and I implemented some systems
that were probably a less efficient way of completing tasks, but often did so in such a way for learning purposes.
I tried to challenge myself with more modern concepts that I didn't learn back in my university days, like enhanced for
loops for example, and probably over used classes to the detriment of development.

High level thoughts coming out of the project:
• Write down your current thought process when you walk away from the computer, as getting back in the mindset
    of what you are working on takes a bit of time and writing down where you left off speeds up that time significantly
• Just start writing code. While planning early and sticking to scope is important, being able to plan for future
    problems will come with experience, and experience doesn't happen without coding. So just start writing, and come
    back and fix compounding errors as needed if required.
• I hope to get better with the IDE to increase speed significantly. Often found myself doing a task, knowing what
    needed to be done, but not knowing the fastest way to complete the task. For example, changing the name of a
    variable was often avoided later in writing a method because of how often the variable was used. I know there's a
    find and replace method / hotkey but could never get it to stick in my brain.
• In the interest of saving time and moving on with the coursework I've stopped short of a few goals. I would have
    enjoyed trying to animate the input screens, clearing the terminal between each frame rather than a scrolling
    screen, but couldn't find the time to do so. I also did no ship sinking validation, which I think is a big loss to
    the gameplay. I wanted to implement some guessing logic to the computer as well, rather than just complete random,
    but ran out of time to do so.

Specific thoughts:
• The Board class has a getColIndex() and getColChar() method that's a big switch statement. I know there's
    mathematically a much better way of doing this, just didn't spend the time figuring it out. Initial thoughts would
    be something similar to how I did the max row and col index math, knowing Char 'A' = 65 or something like that you
    can work backwards to the index, but the switch statement was easy to understand, and fast enough for this project.
    And using a method, I could always change the switch statement to the math and return the value and it would be
    minimal code updating.
• Next time I would probably store more data at the Boat level, and possibly just re-render / calculate the board state
    each time I needed to based on the boat data. Then I can store hit data in the boats, and do the classic "you sunk
    my battleship!" line in the terminal. I could check game state based on a players boats inventory instead of
    counting the board. This would also make the game more expandable, you could have custom boats, custom skills to
    attack more than one square for example, etc etc.
• Implement a while loop in Main.java to loop through the gameplay options would have been a better system. A user
    could also initiate a new game without having to re-launch the program that way.
• I need to do a better job of validating inputs from the user, and from the random computer guesses. There has to be a
    better way than what I was doing.
• The Screen class became more of a controller in the MVC system than I would have liked. I think if I did as I talked
    about above where I stored more data in boats I could have really used the Screen class as a rendering system and
    kept the enums of game state in a separate class.

I had claude code review my project and give me feedback, here's what I've learned:
• I learned a better null input check, mine is out of order @ line 283 in the Screen class, I didn't see that bug while
    running the game, but after input testing it myself I confirmed.
• setBoat() should toggle using this.state = true; and I agree, flipping isn't correct for it's use case.
• I duplicated code in a few places, and knew I was doing it at the time. In an effort to save time implementing I
    copy and pasted the logic rather than pulling it out into it's own method call. In the future once I get better with
    the IDE I think I'll be faster and more logical about pulling out duplicate code into a method.
• checkValidInput is a recursive function. It's better to do that in a while loop, but I did it this way on purpose to
    practice recursivity. Risk of stackOverflowError is understood.
• AI told me in seconds the math for the getColIndex and getColChar... oof
• I need to get better at some naming convention, I didn't know the enum naming convention.
• Computer can re-guess the same square, I knew this but forgot to point it out in specific thoughts above. I think I
    could easily implement a better system there, but have run out of time.